<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="379" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[114,647,972,1305]" box="[114,258,972,998]" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[114,647,972,1305]" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">
From the broken specimens available (the biggest is 
<quantity box="[136,203,1033,1060]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="379" unit="cm" value="10.0">10 cm</quantity>
high and 
<quantity box="[310,363,1033,1060]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="379" unit="cm" value="5.0">5 cm</quantity>
across), the sponge is massive amorphous with large lobate processes and may reach a large size (
<figureCitation box="[355,437,1095,1121]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="10.[114,125,842,859]" captionTargetBox="[128,1201,211,800]" captionTargetId="figure-405@10.[115,1214,195,824]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIG. 8. — Microxina sarai n. sp.; A, paratype; B, skeletal architecture showing the ascending tracts of oxeas forming superficial brushes; C, thin, spicular ectosomal membrane; D, choanosomal skeleton; E, microxea; F, sigma. Scale bars: A, 1 cm; B, 2.5 mm; C, 140 µm; D, 700 µm; E, F, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757731" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757731/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">Fig. 8A</figureCitation>
.) The colour is pale yellow or beige. The sponge is inelastic, tough but very fragile, both wet and dry. The surface is bristly from the protruding spicule brushes. A thin ectosomal membrane is lost in most of the dredged specimens. Oscules are round, slightly raised (
<quantity box="[123,212,1278,1305]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="379" unit="mm" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1-2 mm</quantity>
), with a diameter of 
<quantity box="[430,517,1278,1305]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="379" unit="mm" value="7.0" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="6.0">6-8 mm</quantity>
(
<figureCitation box="[530,613,1279,1305]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="10.[114,125,842,859]" captionTargetBox="[128,1201,211,800]" captionTargetId="figure-405@10.[115,1214,195,824]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIG. 8. — Microxina sarai n. sp.; A, paratype; B, skeletal architecture showing the ascending tracts of oxeas forming superficial brushes; C, thin, spicular ectosomal membrane; D, choanosomal skeleton; E, microxea; F, sigma. Scale bars: A, 1 cm; B, 2.5 mm; C, 140 µm; D, 700 µm; E, F, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757731" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757731/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">Fig. 8A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[114,647,1341,1704]" box="[114,199,1341,1367]" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">
<emphasis box="[114,199,1341,1367]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">Skeleton</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[114,647,1341,1704]" lastBlockId="10.[677,1209,972,1029]" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">
The ectosome is a thin layer of disorderly arranged tangential oxeas with abundant microscleres (
<figureCitation box="[121,210,1433,1459]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="10.[114,125,842,859]" captionTargetBox="[128,1201,211,800]" captionTargetId="figure-405@10.[115,1214,195,824]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIG. 8. — Microxina sarai n. sp.; A, paratype; B, skeletal architecture showing the ascending tracts of oxeas forming superficial brushes; C, thin, spicular ectosomal membrane; D, choanosomal skeleton; E, microxea; F, sigma. Scale bars: A, 1 cm; B, 2.5 mm; C, 140 µm; D, 700 µm; E, F, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757731" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757731/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">Fig. 8C</figureCitation>
). The choanosomal skeleton is formed by multispicular (six to ten) tracts of oxeas which dichotomically divide or merge forming a regular ascending pattern (
<figureCitation box="[330,423,1525,1551]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="10.[114,125,842,859]" captionTargetBox="[128,1201,211,800]" captionTargetId="figure-405@10.[115,1214,195,824]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIG. 8. — Microxina sarai n. sp.; A, paratype; B, skeletal architecture showing the ascending tracts of oxeas forming superficial brushes; C, thin, spicular ectosomal membrane; D, choanosomal skeleton; E, microxea; F, sigma. Scale bars: A, 1 cm; B, 2.5 mm; C, 140 µm; D, 700 µm; E, F, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757731" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757731/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">Fig. 8D</figureCitation>
). Primary tracts are connected by oxeas (one to three) thus forming a loose reticulation with scarce spongin. In proximity of the sponge surface, the ascending tracts diverge to form tufts of oxeas (
<figureCitation box="[473,559,1647,1673]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="10.[114,125,842,859]" captionTargetBox="[128,1201,211,800]" captionTargetId="figure-405@10.[115,1214,195,824]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIG. 8. — Microxina sarai n. sp.; A, paratype; B, skeletal architecture showing the ascending tracts of oxeas forming superficial brushes; C, thin, spicular ectosomal membrane; D, choanosomal skeleton; E, microxea; F, sigma. Scale bars: A, 1 cm; B, 2.5 mm; C, 140 µm; D, 700 µm; E, F, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757731" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757731/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">Fig. 8B</figureCitation>
) which penetrate the dermal membrane. Interstitial oxeas and microscleres are abundant, also in the choanosome.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[677,1210,1065,1459]" box="[677,757,1065,1091]" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">
<emphasis box="[677,757,1065,1091]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">Spicules</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[677,1210,1065,1459]" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">
Oxeas straight or slightly curved (
<figureCitation box="[1026,1107,1095,1121]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="11.[113,124,723,740]" captionTargetBox="[98,1222,206,685]" captionTargetId="figure-501@11.[94,1228,195,693]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIG. 9. — Microxina sarai n. sp.; A, oxeas; B, small sigmas; C, big, open sigmas; D, microxeas. Scale bars: A, 100 µm; B-D, 50 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757733/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">Fig. 9A</figureCitation>
), measuring 209-382 (278.9) × 14-20 (17.3) µm. Slender forms, which are always straight and generally longer than average are rather frequent (
<figureCitation box="[1097,1180,1187,1213]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="11.[113,124,723,740]" captionTargetBox="[98,1222,206,685]" captionTargetId="figure-501@11.[94,1228,195,693]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIG. 9. — Microxina sarai n. sp.; A, oxeas; B, small sigmas; C, big, open sigmas; D, microxeas. Scale bars: A, 100 µm; B-D, 50 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757733/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">Fig. 9A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[677,1210,1065,1459]" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">
Sigmas occur in two categories. Small sigmas are thin and more closed: 16-24 (25.3) × 1-2 µm (
<figureCitation box="[684,773,1279,1305]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="10.[114,125,842,859]" captionTargetBox="[128,1201,211,800]" captionTargetId="figure-405@10.[115,1214,195,824]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIG. 8. — Microxina sarai n. sp.; A, paratype; B, skeletal architecture showing the ascending tracts of oxeas forming superficial brushes; C, thin, spicular ectosomal membrane; D, choanosomal skeleton; E, microxea; F, sigma. Scale bars: A, 1 cm; B, 2.5 mm; C, 140 µm; D, 700 µm; E, F, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757731" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757731/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">Figs 8F</figureCitation>
; 
<figureCitation box="[787,822,1279,1305]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="11.[113,124,723,740]" captionTargetBox="[98,1222,206,685]" captionTargetId="figure-501@11.[94,1228,195,693]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIG. 9. — Microxina sarai n. sp.; A, oxeas; B, small sigmas; C, big, open sigmas; D, microxeas. Scale bars: A, 100 µm; B-D, 50 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757733/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">9B</figureCitation>
). Large sigmas are slightly thicker and more open in shape (
<figureCitation box="[1007,1109,1310,1336]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="11.[113,124,723,740]" captionTargetBox="[98,1222,206,685]" captionTargetId="figure-501@11.[94,1228,195,693]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIG. 9. — Microxina sarai n. sp.; A, oxeas; B, small sigmas; C, big, open sigmas; D, microxeas. Scale bars: A, 100 µm; B-D, 50 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757733/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">Fig. 9C</figureCitation>
): 36-62 (45.9) × 1-3 µm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[677,1210,1065,1459]" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">
Microxeas straight or very slightly curved, sometimes with the tips bent back (
<figureCitation box="[1000,1084,1402,1428]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="10.[114,125,842,859]" captionTargetBox="[128,1201,211,800]" captionTargetId="figure-405@10.[115,1214,195,824]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIG. 8. — Microxina sarai n. sp.; A, paratype; B, skeletal architecture showing the ascending tracts of oxeas forming superficial brushes; C, thin, spicular ectosomal membrane; D, choanosomal skeleton; E, microxea; F, sigma. Scale bars: A, 1 cm; B, 2.5 mm; C, 140 µm; D, 700 µm; E, F, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757731" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757731/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">Figs 8E</figureCitation>
; 
<figureCitation box="[1095,1134,1402,1428]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="11.[113,124,723,740]" captionTargetBox="[98,1222,206,685]" captionTargetId="figure-501@11.[94,1228,195,693]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIG. 9. — Microxina sarai n. sp.; A, oxeas; B, small sigmas; C, big, open sigmas; D, microxeas. Scale bars: A, 100 µm; B-D, 50 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757733/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">9D</figureCitation>
). They measure 50-80 (62.8) × 1-2 µm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="380" pageId="10" pageNumber="379" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[677,1210,1493,1704]" box="[677,777,1493,1519]" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[677,1210,1493,1704]" lastBlockId="11.[113,647,788,1213]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="380" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">
The new species is placed in 
<taxonomicName authority="Topsent, 1916" authorityName="Topsent" authorityYear="1916" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="10" pageNumber="379" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[999,1107,1524,1549]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="379">Microxina</emphasis>
Topsent, 1916
</taxonomicName>
based on its choanosomal skeleton with characteristic polyspicular tracts ending in superficial tufts and presence of microxeas and sigmas as microscleres. The presence of a thin ectosomal membrane with tangential oxeas is an important character of 
<taxonomicName authority="Calcinai &amp; Pansini, 2000" authorityName="Calcinai &amp; Pansini" authorityYear="2000" box="[251,340,788,813]" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="11" pageNumber="380" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="sarai" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[251,340,788,813]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="380">M. sarai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[349,410,788,814]" pageId="11" pageNumber="380" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
that is not shared by the other species in this genus. Two other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Topsent" authorityYear="1916" box="[145,255,849,874]" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="11" pageNumber="380" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[145,255,849,874]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="380">Microxina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with microxeas as microscleres are known from the Antarctic: 
<taxonomicName authority="(Topsent, 1901)" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Topsent" baseAuthorityYear="1901" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="11" pageNumber="380" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="benedeni">
<emphasis box="[408,537,880,907]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="380">M. benedeni</emphasis>
(Topsent, 1901)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Topsent, 1916)" baseAuthorityName="Topsent" baseAuthorityYear="1916" box="[245,573,911,937]" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="11" pageNumber="380" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="simplex">
<emphasis box="[245,369,911,937]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="380">M. simplex</emphasis>
(Topsent, 1916)
</taxonomicName>
. They share with the new species the structure of the choanosomal skeleton, but the polyspicular tracts (15-20 oxeas) are much stouter and the oxea size is at least twice as big. Also their external morphology is different because they have an uneven surface covered by long slender processes (especially in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Topsent" baseAuthorityYear="1901" box="[210,343,1125,1152]" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="11" pageNumber="380" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="benedeni">
<emphasis box="[210,343,1125,1152]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="380">M. benedeni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) that gives them a peculiar spiny appearance. Several specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Topsent" baseAuthorityYear="1901" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="11" pageNumber="380" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="benedeni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="380">M. benedeni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were recorded from Terra Nova Bay.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
