<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="380" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="11.[113,647,1248,1551]" box="[113,217,1248,1274]" pageId="11" pageNumber="380">ECOLOGY</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[113,647,1248,1551]" pageId="11" pageNumber="380">
The species is abundant on the continental shelf of Terra Nova Bay between 95 and 
<quantity box="[503,576,1309,1336]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="11" pageNumber="380" unit="m" value="110.0">110 m</quantity>
depth on hard bottoms with a clear sponge predominance (Cattaneo-Vietti 
<emphasis box="[398,448,1371,1397]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="380">et al</emphasis>
. 1999b). It may attain a remarkable size (at least 
<quantity box="[464,532,1401,1428]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="380" unit="cm" value="30.0">30 cm</quantity>
in height) as seen on the R.O.V. videos but since it looks very similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Topsent, 1901)" baseAuthorityName="Topsent" baseAuthorityYear="1901" box="[284,646,1463,1489]" class="Demospongiae" family="Niphatidae" genus="Microxina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="11" pageNumber="380" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="rudis">
<emphasis box="[284,457,1463,1489]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="380">Microxina rudis</emphasis>
(Topsent, 1901)
</taxonomicName>
in the same area, the image interpretation requires caution.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
